{
  "In the Leontief input-output model, the equation x = Cx + d is used. What does the vector d represent?": "",
  "External (final) demand": "",
  "The price vector": "",
  "Total production": "",
  "The consumption matrix": "",
  "In the Leontief model x = Cx + d, the vector d represents the external demand from consumers, government, and exports that must be met after inter-industry consumption.": "",
  "To solve the Leontief equation x = Cx + d for x, which formula is used?": "",
  "x = d - Cx": "",
  "x = C^(-1) d": "",
  "x = (I + C)d": "",
  "x = (I - C)^(-1) d": "",
  "Rearranging x = Cx + d gives (I - C)x = d, so x = (I - C)^(-1) d, provided (I - C) is invertible.": "",
  "In a two-sector economy, sector 1 uses 0.2 of its own output and 0.3 of sector 2's output per dollar produced. What entry goes in position (1,1) of the consumption matrix C?": "",
  "0.5": "",
  "1.0": "",
  "0.3": "",
  "0.2": "",
  "Entry c_{11} = 0.2 represents the amount of sector 1's output consumed by sector 1 itself per dollar of sector 1 production.": "",
  "A simple supply-demand model has: supply S = 2p + 10 and demand D = -3p + 60. At equilibrium (S = D), what is the price p?": "",
  "14": "",
  "5": "",
  "8": "",
  "10": "",
  "Setting S = D: 2p + 10 = -3p + 60, so 5p = 50 and p = 10. The equilibrium quantity is S = 2(10) + 10 = 30.": "",
  "In a market with two goods, the equilibrium conditions give the system: 3p1 - p2 = 10 and -p1 + 4p2 = 20. What is p1?": "",
  "70/11": "",
  "10/3": "",
  "60/11": "",
  "From equation 1: p2 = 3p1 - 10. Substitute into equation 2: -p1 + 4(3p1 - 10) = 20, so 11p1 = 60, p1 = 60/11.": "",
  "If a consumption matrix C has all column sums less than 1, what does this guarantee?": "",
  "The economy produces nothing": "",
  "The determinant of C is zero": "",
  "(I - C) is invertible and (I - C)^(-1) has all nonnegative entries": "",
  "There is no equilibrium": "",
  "When each column of C sums to less than 1, each sector consumes less than it produces. The matrix (I - C) is invertible with a nonnegative inverse, ensuring a feasible production vector for any demand d >= 0.": "",
